Insurrection: Hundreds of Years Worth of Tension

by Caitlyn Meisner and Benjamin Fikhman

Protestors holding a “Jesus Saves” flag in front of the U.S. Capitol on January 6th. (Tyler Merbler)

“America is the best country in the world. F**king libs are ruining it,” – an honest and candid response when asked what American culture or heritage meant to an individual from a survey conducted. Although the answers differed across a diverse group of Americans, similar ideals were represented: freedom, liberty, and diversity. No one answer was the same, but regardless of their political affiliation, these Americans could agree on the fundamentals of the country they live in. Many responses highlighted the diversity the United States has, giving the

American people the “opportunity to explore the melting pot of different cultures combined into one nation,” or allowing Americans to possess “certain ideals” from the Constitution, but “holding their own ethnic values.” While the diversity of the U.S. is being praised, the hostile political climate proves there are deeper issues to be discussed. Nobody could agree on one issue within the two-party system today; responses ranged from blaming both Democrats and

Republicans to criticizing the other party for halting legislation, radicalizing groups of Americans, or even serving as an existential threat.

The American people are demonstrating a deep concern for this country’s current political climate, especially after the largest attack on the United States Capitol just a little over seven months ago on January 6th, 2021. The attack exemplified the culmination of political and religious tensions that have plagued this country since its inception. There is no denying the role conservatism - or Trumpism - played in this event growing to the magnitude it did, trapping citizens all across the nation in front of their television screens and radios, wondering if America’s top political leaders will survive. Examining this event through a detailed historical background and an in-depth survey from Americans will expose the deeply rooted issues and history of conservatism and Christianity as they pertain to the health of a modern politic.

Wilmington, North Carolina

“Negro rule is a curse.” That was written in The Democratic Handbook of 1898, outlining the official platform of the Democratic Party of North Carolina. Parallels with what unfolded in and around the nation’s Capitol this year were displayed in their full, devastating form in 1898. A real and successful coup d’etat took place in Wilmington; where white supremacists coerced Republican politicians into resignation, consequently massacring innocent Black Americans in what was once a majority Black city. The horrific tragedy is similar to the Tulsa Massacre of June 1921, in that African-Americans have been, yet again, painted as instigators or collateral damage. The tragedy of Wilmington is likewise seldom discussed in the books of academia.

Racial resentment, fear, and hatred were the impetus for the mob violence in the North Carolinian city, demonstrating that the hostility is conspicuous within the historical revisionism that attempts to twist or remove that day from public awareness. Slavery was abolished a few decades before the tragedy in Wilmington, but the influences that drove and justified white supremacy never left, which includes the weaponization of Christianity. Biblical literalism and a sense of there being a “God’s Plan” was deployed in a manner that established a clear and simple racial hierarchy. Emeritus history professor at the University of North Carolina in Wilmington said, “While some of [the attack] was secular, much of it was biblically based with a low-church Protestant view of slavery.” The insurrection at the U.S. Capitol earlier this year saw a similar brand of exclusionary, racial nationalism that was ignited by fears of incoming demographic change. Wilmington’s status as a majority Black city in 1898 was taken as a threat to those who participated in the coup d’etat; racial and theological justifications of white supremacy were used to kick on the door of democracy - the American ideal blatantly repressed by the rioters. The underpinnings of racial animosity emphasized the aspect of an existential threat, which was used to justify the sidestepping of democratic process.

Similar trends occurred in the lead-up to the Tulsa Race Massacre of 1921. Hannibal B. Johnson’s article “Tulsa, Then and Now,” the Ku Klux Klan made its presence known. This notorious white supremacist cult grew exponentially in Oklahoma during the 1920s.

Newspapers, the media of the day, fanned the flames of racial discord. The Tulsa Tribune, a daily afternoon newspaper, published a series of inflammatory articles and editorials that denigrated Tulsa's Black citizens and fomented anti-Black hostility among white Tulsans.

The Birth of Conservatism and Christianity as a Unit

The years following the controversial Watergate scandal were difficult to navigate. After the resignation of Former President Richard Nixon, America desperately needed a true, American leader. In 1976, Jimmy Carter was elected as a Baptist Democrat, but his popularity did not last long with religious voters. During the late 1970s, the rise of white evangelicalism took over the United States. Ronald Reagan clinched the presidency with two-thirds of the vote from white evangelical voters.1 During its time, it was called the “New Christian Right,” with millions of Protestants, Catholics, and Mormons joining forces within one conservative political bloc.2

Even in 1982, the Christian Right was described as “extreme and passionate,” calling for total commitment, and can be “apocalyptic.”3 This is no mistake; the creation of the Moral Majority by Jerry Falwell sealed the enduring relationship between conservatism and Christianity. The Moral Majority was composed of conservative Christians lobbying for religion in public schools, rejection of the Equal Rights Amendment, and other social issues that were controversial in the 1980s. Typical of conservative beliefs, Falwell emphasized his hostility to abortion and homosexuality, cementing the Moral Majority’s stance on social change. After losing a sense of self within conservatism and Republicans, the Moral Majority and Ronald Reagan revived the party’s agenda as a strong, unapologetically American force to be reckoned with.

While the relationship between conservatism and Christianity mainly represented whites in the 1980s, it has increased its number of minority groups in recent years. Trump’s large base of older, white Evangelicals is not uncharacteristic: this specific group has rallied for Republicans since Reagan.3 Trump promised with his slogan to “Make America Great Again,” reminiscing on times where whites were the majority and had power over other minority groups.

Much of the minority vote is fueled by the GOP’s focus on economic growth in contrast with the Democratic Party’s focus on “woke progressivism.”4 Many of the voters of minority ethnic groups do not see themselves as needing vindication against white America, not even considering themselves minorities at all.

Yet, “woke progressivism” is still seen as a sort of boogeyman by many on the right, particularly those who share a reverence for an American Christian heritage. In our survey of 58 Baylor University students, several students with “far-right,” “right-leaning,” or “Republican” identifications, Christians in particular, have expressed common grievances about the threat “woke progressivism” poses to America. In response to the survey question, “What does

Modern Conservative Christian America

While the days of the Reagan presidency are over, current Republicans remain strongly tied with the Christian sect of the United States. More recently, former President Donald Trump possessed a heavily loyal base of white Evangelicals. In the notorious 2016 election, Trump’s support from Evangelicals was at a shocking 80%, even higher than George W. Bush.5 Although Trump is not considered to be the typical God-fearing man - with his multiple marriages, cheating scandals, and vulgar speech - the way he speaks truly resonates with the white Evangelicals across the United States. He voices their inner fear that the country they love is slipping away due to modernization; the influx of immigrants, acceptance of LGBTQ+ rights, and the increase in awareness towards religious and racial minorities represent the ever-changing society they do not want.6 While the base of Evangelicals has increasingly diversified, a majority still remains white and in their 50s and 60s: largely making the Republican Party representative of 70-year-old America.7 Trump’s “Make America Great Again” slogan resonated with the older crowd, as it signified a desire to return to the less diverse era of the 1950s.9

Charlottesville, Virginia: Radicalization and Pretext for Worse to Come

Charlottesville, Virginia was rated by National Geographic as the 3rd happiest American city in 2017, but during the summer of the same year, it was also the site of the “Unite the Right” rally that spanned from August 11-12, still having a deep imprint on the American psyche. Racial vitriol and fear-mongering enveloped the far-right coalition that participated. Chants of “white lives matter” were heard, a direct mockery of the Black Lives Matter movement’s struggle for widespread recognition of the persistence of systemic racism. “Jews will not replace us” evoked the centuries-long message of an anti-Semitic “replacement theory.” And, of course, there was “blood and soil” heard among the Klansmen, Neo-Nazis, the alt-right, and other participants in a

The Infamous Insurrection

January 6th, 2021, a day in the United States that was meant to end claims of a fraudulent presidential election. At 12:53 p.m. EST, that all changed; the day U.S. history will forever look at as a permanent stain upon American democracy. This day was a culmination of frustration from conservative, Christian America due to the tumultuous year that was 2020: a global pandemic, contentious presidential election, and a constant attack of their values.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic that halted abilities for in-person voting for millions of voters, mail-in ballots grew in importance. In April 2020, 7 whole months before Election Day, Trump was already questioning the validity of this form of voting, claiming that they “[were] a very dangerous thing for this country” and ultimately will rig the election itself.8 After results came back that Joe Biden had clinched the presidency, Trump launched many baseless lawsuits claiming fraud and refusing to concede to his incoming successor. Typical of every presidential election, there is a joint session of Congress to confirm the next president that would be elected just two weeks later on January 20th. This joint session is usually just a formality, but the 2020 election and the state of the country depended on this running smoothly. Tensions were ramping up to this day; House members were claiming they would object to Biden’s confirmation, as well as Trump begging the Georgia Secretary of State to alter voting results in favor of himself.9

Coined as the “Save America March,” Trump promptly primed a group of his enraged supporters for chaos. Standing outside the White House during Congress’ joint session, former President Trump opened his rally with a prayer, calling upon God to grace his base with “holy boldness in the next hour.”10 The former president’s spiritual advisor, Paula White, asked God to deliver the overturn of “every adversary against democracy, freedom, [and] justice in the name of Jesus:” so they did.11 Just moments later, thousands traveled from the White House to the Capitol to “stop the steal;” these so-called patriots beat police, smashed windows, broke down doors, and breached the Senate chambers long enough to pray in Christ’s name for allowing them to have a hand in the rebirth of their country.12 While not all rioters and protesters there showed up in the name of Jesus, many of them still believed that Donald Trump was anointed by God Himself. His base of old, white Evangelicals was under the assumption that Trump was meant to restore the United States as a Christian nation.15 Several prominent Christian political leaders coordinated group meetings at the insurrection, leading to their subsequent arrests.

Apocalyptic Conservatism

As paradoxical as it may seem, conservative Christians in America are largely fearsome of the future. Even though they trust their Lord to lead them safely to Heaven or their afterlife, they are frightened by something they can actually shape: the future. Not in a college student fearful of their future post-grad way, but more of a fear related to the state of the country in terms of its rapid modernity and diversity. While modern America is focused on diversifying the government, promoting acceptance of all, and making steps towards equality, many white

Christians are refusing to participate. Most recently, common Christian rhetoric during the COVID-19 pandemic echoes the idea that “God is sovereign over [the] virus,” absolving the government of responsibility in protecting Americans against the virus itself.13 Studies have even

Although churches have great influence on their members, social media and news sites have cultivated the apocalyptic conversative Christian mentality that some possess. Conspiracy theories surrounding government have been rampant with the rise of social media, but especially with the popularization of QAnon, a far-right, loosely organized network of believers that embrace, spread, and defend unsubstantiated beliefs about society and the government.18 QAnon believers are under the assumption that two large events - the Storm and the Great Awakening will soon come and prove “Q’s” theories were right all along.19 “Q” is believed to be the ringleader of QAnon itself, who is speculated to be a high-ranking government official spreading information from the inside, but most importantly, regarded as a patriot.14 Upon first glance, this conspiracy group may seem harmless and ignorable - but it is anything but. Radical QAnon believers demonstrate traits comparable to dangerous cults: sacrificing their individuality for a “greater good,” shunning their families, and identifying with a calling to participate in an ominous movement.21 QAnon followers are not opposed to using religious images and figures to justify their claims, often blending religious and cult-like tactics to radicalize believers.

Cults and conspiracy groups can be isolated and run in their own circles, but QAnon has placed itself right on center stage. In the rising tensions of a controversial election and devastating global pandemic, QAnon flourished in spreading theories. Well after the election results had been settled in President Joe Biden’s favor, QAnon followers and Trump supporters alike would not stand for these results. While QAnon cannot take full blame, the conspiracy theory assuredly contributed to the magnitude of the Capitol riots. At least 66 QAnon followers committed violent acts either before, during, or after the Capitol insurrection on January 6th.15Although the investigation and arrests are not over, 34 out of 400 arrested rioters are connected to QAnon - demonstrating their true influence over Americans to act violently under the assumption that they are acting in good faith.23

The doomsday mindset of Christians is not new; many white Evangelicals have been blaming other religions for their downfall. The Christian persecution complex - the belief that Christians and their values are being oppressed by social groups and governments - runs rampant throughout the United States. This fear is quite interesting since every president that has ever been elected in the United States has been some form of Christian denomination whether it was Episcopalian, Catholic, Presbyterian, or one of the other denominations.18 Although the representation, numbers, and voices are highly regarded, white Evangelicals are thought to be the minority in their own minds: quite the dangerous mindset to have.

This is Not the End

The Capitol insurrection on January 6th is the perfect demonstration of what can occur after years of political tension, growing rejection, and battles from the lowest to the highest parts of society. Looking back at what happened in Wilmington, North Carolina in the late 1800s, it is no shock that these attitudes are old as time; what’s shocking is that these attitudes, beliefs, and actions still exist so prevalently close to 250 years later. One can only hope that an increase in diversity and forcible change will alter these attitudes, but that has shown to only make it worse or even incite this violence. Violent, conservative Christians who refuse to accept the progression of time and its consequences are the symptom of a complex intertwinement of church and state in the United States. With every president being some form of Christian, with barely any Supreme Court justices being anything other than Christian or Jewish, and the idea of God infiltrating many fundamental documents in the U.S., it is difficult to see a light at the end of the tunnel where America is completely separated. But, many surveyors demonstrated their concern and love for their country despite their religious or political affiliation. Surveyors across the board agreed there were issues with the American political climate, but not necessarily defining a culture that is definitely American. Some stated the U.S. is fundamentally based in freedom, liberty, and justice, but a majority responded with two words: melting pot. The United States may have majority races, religions, sexual orientations, or genders, but there is no one definitive culture. American culture is just that: a melting pot.
